    "thinking": "The user is saying I shouldn't worry about keeping the intake-* and loe-* naming convention. They're flexible on the field IDs. Their other app (which sends data to S1/S2) can be updated to match whatever field IDs make sense for this system.\n\nSo the question is: what's the cleanest field naming approach?\n\nOption 1: Keep intake-* and loe-* prefixes\n- Pro: Clear that these are source fields from S1/S2\n- Con: Creates duplicate naming (intake-client-first-name vs client-first-name)\n\nOption 2: Use clean canonical names, no prefix\n- Pro: One field ID everywhere (client-first-name is client-first-name)\n- Pro: Simpler - no mapping/translation needed\n- Pro: Template uses same ID as registry\n- Con: Need to know which section it's in by looking at section property\n\nI think Option 2 is cleaner. The section property already tells us where it belongs. We don't need the prefix.\n\nSo instead of:\n- intake-client-first-name (S1)\n- client-name (Cover) \n\nWe just have:\n- client-first-name (section: client-intake)\n- client-last-name (section: client-intake)\n- client-email (section: client-intake)\n\nAnd the template uses {{client-first-name}} {{client-last-name}} or we have a computed client-full-name.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully...\n\nActually, the cleanest approach:\n1. Use simple, canonical field IDs without prefixes\n2. The `section` property determines which tab it appears in\n3. No duplication - one field ID per concept\n4. Template placeholders match field IDs directly\n\nSo the field consolidation becomes:\n\nClient info (section: client-intake):\n- client-first-name\n- client-last-name  \n- client-email\n- client-phone\n- client-title\n\n\n- client-organization\n- client-address\n- client-city\n- client-province\n- client-postal\n\nI'll continue consolidating fields with a clean, consistent naming strategy. The goal is to create a straightforward, intuitive field structure that clearly indicates the data's purpose without unnecessary prefixes. Each field will have a unique, descriptive ID that works across different sections of the form.\n\nProperty details follow a similar pattern, using clear, concise identifiers that immediately convey their meaning. The section property will handle categorization, eliminating the need for complex naming conventions.\n\nThe approach ensures clarity, reduces redundancy, and makes the form's structure more maintainable and easy to understand at a glance.",
